b"\xe2\x80\x9cKovu is also a huge motivation for me. I want to win so I can provide him the best life ever,\xe2\x80\x9d says World Champion track and field star, Kori Carter. 

While traveling and competing across the world, Kovu has always kept her grounded. \xe2\x80\x9cHe's always at my side. He's my piece of stability in my life because my life is a little crazy.\xe2\x80\x9d Carter says Kovu helps her cope with the changes. 

During the COVID-19 outbreak, Kovu\xe2\x80\x99s support became even more important. When the 2020 Tokyo Games were postponed to 2021 and most major sports competitions were canceled, Carter once again relied on her companion. He serves as a reminder that she is needed off the track. \xe2\x80\x9cI still have some sort of purpose without being able to go to competitions,\xe2\x80\x9d she says. \xe2\x80\x9cKovu is my little source of joy every day.\xe2\x80\x9d She utilized her time in quarantine by building a dog house as a hangout space for Kovu, complete with a succulent garden, bed, turf floor and wall planter. 

Read up and learn more about @thekorimonster and her unbreakable bond with her pup, Kovu, in bio."

b'Meet Trent Allen aka The Cat Whisperer // \xe2\x80\x9cI have this patience level with animals, this deeper understanding from watching very subtle changes in their body language. I understand their pain, because I\xe2\x80\x99ve gone through pain myself,\xe2\x80\x9d says Allen, reflecting on his experience coming out as transgender.

Allen specializes in comforting and socializing difficult felines, training them to accept care and love so that they\xe2\x80\x99re able to find an adopted family. He finds joy in socializing shelter cats, and helping the animals become \xe2\x80\x9ccomfortable in their own skin\xe2\x80\x9d by giving them a haircut and a bath. Since he began working at the shelter about a year and a half ago, he\xe2\x80\x99s helped to rehabilitate over 150 cats and fostered over 40 in his own home. 

Check out some of our other Heroes of the Month in collaboration with @adoptapetcom. Link in bio to learn more. #ChewyGivesBack'

b'Meet 13-year-old Sir Darius Brown, the kid who has turned his hand sewn bow ties into a lifesaving tool to help pets get adopted.

Sir Darius estimates he\xe2\x80\x99s made and donated nearly 400 bow ties to animals in need, with plans to donate another 300 this August alone. In addition to the ASPCA in New York City, he\xe2\x80\x99s mailed them to shelters all across the U.S., from Virginia and Pennsylvania to Illinois and Michigan. He\xe2\x80\x99s even sent bow ties to shelters in the United Kingdom. Sir Darius also posts photos of shelter pets wearing his bow ties to his Instagram page, advocating for their adoption to his more than 60,000 followers. b'In uncertain times, there\'s one thing we can be certain about. Our world is a better place with pets. Many animal welfare organizations are left without basic supplies, and pet food is in especially high demand. By joining forces we\'ve already donated over $2.2 million in pet essentials to aid rescues and shelters across the nation.\n\nOur CEO said it best, "We remain dedicated to our partners operating on the frontlines of the current situation and will continue to look for ways to donate more. By partnering with GreaterGood.org, we are able to direct resources to pets in highly impacted regions who need it most." We are proud to work alongside @greatergoodorg and hope that our donation makes it possible for many shelters to continue to move onward. Or, simply, inspires all of you to put more good out into the world\xe2\x80\x94 whether it\'s checking in on a fellow pet parent, or brightening a Zoom meeting with a dog. b'Dr. Dani McVety and Dr. Mary Gardner do what might be the hardest thing vets can do: help animals pass. As founders of @lapofloveveterinaryhospice, they oversee a national network of veterinarians focused on family-oriented hospice and in-home euthanasia services. \nThey focus on helping make a pet\xe2\x80\x99s final weeks and days as comfortable as possible, and helping pet parents decide what the best avenue is for an aging or injured pet. Sometimes that means delivering hard news to pet parents. \nMcVety says, \xe2\x80\x9cI\xe2\x80\x99m often telling people, \xe2\x80\x98We\xe2\x80\x99re either going to do a $4,000 surgery, or we\xe2\x80\x99re going to euthanize, and the only wrong answer is doing nothing at all.\xe2\x80\x99\xe2\x80\x9d #IWD2020 #EachforEqual'

b'Janet Donlin\xe2\x80\x99s love for animals started at an early age. She was a city mouse who also loved country mice. \nIn 2010, she became the first woman CEO of the American Veterinary Medical Association. She says, \xe2\x80\x9cI can\xe2\x80\x99t think of a more rewarding and wonderful career than veterinary medicine\xe2\x80\xa6 it\xe2\x80\x99s wonderful to be able to work with people who value and appreciate the human-animal bond and that unconditional love [from a pet].\xe2\x80\x9d #IWD2020 #EachforEqual'

b'This week, we\xe2\x80\x99re celebrating female veterinarians who\xe2\x80\x99ve blazed their own trails\xe2\x80\x94and forever changed the future for pets and people alike.

Dr. Jane Hinton didn\xe2\x80\x99t set out to change the face of the veterinary field, but she made history twice. She graduated from the University of Pennsylvania in 1948 as one of the first two African-American women to earn her VMD (Veterinariae Medicinae Doctoris). Before that, as a lab technician at Harvard, she co-developed an agar test that is still used the world over for the diagnosis of infectious diseases. 
Dr. Shelley Rankin, Professor of Clinical Microbiology at the University of Pennsylvania, says, \xe2\x80\x9cThe medium that she helped develop has become the cornerstone of antibiotic susceptibility testing worldwide.\xe2\x80\x9d #IWD2020 #EachforEqual'

b'This week, we\xe2\x80\x99re celebrating female veterinarians who\xe2\x80\x99ve blazed their own trails\xe2\x80\x94and forever changed the future for pets and people alike.

Meet Dr. Elinor McGrath. She patched up animals and busted down doors to become the first female vet in the U.S. As the first woman admitted to the Chicago Vet College in 1907, she was bullied and harassed and considered dropping out, but she stuck it out and graduated with a DVM. 
In the 1910s she started the first woman-owned vet clinic and was a pioneer in the science of pet med. McGrath historian Juliette Fassett says, \xe2\x80\x9cI think she deserves a place in the history books.\xe2\x80\x9d #IWD2020 #EachforEqual'
